post_cb({"30092293": {"ViewCount": "108", "Body": "<p>When I read some questions, I find people prefer to use something like \"<em>\u00a7 27.7.3.6.2/1 [ostream.inserters.arithmetic]</em>\" to describe their question.I believe it has something related to C++.</p>\n<p>Here is the link address of that question:\n<a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26210379/formatted-output-arithmetic-inserters\">Formatted output arithmetic inserters</a></p>\n<p>What I want to ask is: What does \"<em>\u00a7 27.7.3.6.2/1</em>\" refer to? Does it mean a book or something else? If it is a book, please tell me the name of that book.</p>\n", "Title": "What does \"\u00a7 27.7.3.6.2/1\" refers to?", "CreationDate": "2015-05-07T04:59:44.793", "LastActivityDate": "2015-08-03T03:01:53.917", "CommentCount": "0", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T11:43:53.197", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "Id": "30092293", "Score": "5", "OwnerUserId": "3693750", "Tags": "<c++><language-lawyer>", "AnswerCount": "5"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_30092293_30092348_0": {"length": 41, "quality": 0.9318181818181818, "section_id": 2290}}, "n3337": {"so_30092293_30092348_0": {"length": 41, "quality": 0.9318181818181818, "section_id": 2277}}, "n4659": {"so_30092293_30092348_0": {"length": 41, "quality": 0.9318181818181818, "section_id": 2563}}}, "30092334": {"Id": "30092334", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>They're refering to the <a href=\"https://isocpp.org/std/the-standard\" rel=\"nofollow\">C++ standard</a>.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2015-05-07T05:02:55.133", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2015-05-07T05:02:55.133", "ParentId": "30092293", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "180275"}, "30092381": {"Id": "30092381", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It refers to the C++ standard, also known as \"ISO/IEC 14882\", an official document published by ISO that specifies the syntax and semantics of the standard C++ language.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately the standard is actually more expensive than most books, but you can find drafts online that are close to the official standards. See: <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/81656/where-do-i-find-the-current-c-or-c-standard-documents\">Where do I find the current C or C++ standard documents?</a></p>\n<p>So far there have been four standards, published in 1998, 2003, 2011, and 2014, hence the names C++98, C++03, C++11, and C++14. The OP of the other question didn't specify which revision they're referring to. I checked both the 2011 and 2014 standards, and they both have the given quote at the given paragraph number.</p>\n<p>The numerical reference, \"27.7.3.6.2/1\", may change from one revision to the next. \"[ostream.inserters.arithmetic]/1\" is more stable, since the section names don't change, but paragraph numbers and wording might still change, so it's important to specify which revision you're referring to.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastActivityDate": "2015-05-07T05:07:45.257", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2015-05-07T05:07:45.257", "ParentId": "30092293", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "481267", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T12:29:50.933"}, "30092315": {"Id": "30092315", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It refers to the section of the document which is getting referred. In the linked question they are referring to <a href=\"https://isocpp.org/std/the-standard\" rel=\"nofollow\">C++ standard</a>.</p>\n<p>To make it more clear its just like an index in your book which you generally use to refer for fast retrieval. You refer to any particular section by going through that.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "1501794", "LastActivityDate": "2015-05-07T05:05:49.183", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2015-05-07T05:01:25.723", "ParentId": "30092293", "CommentCount": "5", "OwnerUserId": "1501794", "LastEditDate": "2015-05-07T05:05:49.183"}, "30092348": {"Id": "30092348", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>When you're talking about standardised languages like C and C++, it generally refers to the section in the standard (ISO C++ in this case). <code>\u00a7 27.7.3.6.2/1</code> means section <code>27.7.3.6.2</code>, part <code>1</code> of that section.</p>\n<p>In C++11, that particular section is:</p>\n<pre><code>27.7.3.6.2 Arithmetic inserters [ostream.inserters.arithmetic]\n</code></pre>\n<p>and part 1 of it states:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_30092293_30092348_0\"><strong>1</strong> Effects: The classes <code>num_get&lt;&gt;</code> and <code>num_put&lt;&gt;</code> handle locale-dependent numeric formatting and parsing. These inserter functions use the imbued locale value to perform numeric formatting. When <code>val</code> is of type <code>bool</code>, <code>long</code>, <code>unsigned long</code>, <code>long long</code>, <code>unsigned long long</code>, <code>double</code>, <code>long double</code>, or <code>const void*</code>, the formatting conversion occurs as if it performed the following code fragment:</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>... and so on.</p>\n<p>You can get the final versions of the standards (at a cost usually) from your local standards body though you can generally get the final drafts for free on the net that are close to the final versions (although, to be honest, I'm not entirely certain as to the copyright status of these drafts).</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "14860", "LastActivityDate": "2015-05-07T05:10:50.517", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2015-05-07T05:04:28.957", "ParentId": "30092293", "CommentCount": "1", "OwnerUserId": "14860", "LastEditDate": "2015-05-07T05:10:50.517"}, "30092355": {"Id": "30092355", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>In this case, it references a part of the <a href=\"https://isocpp.org/std/the-standard\" rel=\"nofollow\">C++ ISO standard</a>. </p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2015-05-07T05:04:59.840", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2015-05-07T05:04:59.840", "ParentId": "30092293", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "2060725"}});